arch:property.oc:show_val: Locus 75 is the west “platform” between Locus 25 and Locus 29 against Locus 73, resting on dirt. It is simply one course of small hewn or dressed sandstone ashlars organized in two rows. The function of this “platform” and its mirror (Locus 74) is not at all clear. It is clearly related in some way to Locus 25 and the rubble walls Loci 29 and 73, but none of these features are understood fully. Like those walls, it is tentatively phase to Stage 4 because of its construction style and obvious later date than the original construction of the bath complex.

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
1.54 m north south -by- 0.45 m east west.
